  "text": "To highlight the regional diversity of the precipitation threshold, threshold values of MaxR in every 2.5°(latitude) by 2.5°(longitude) box over the globe are calculated based on CPR observations for four years (2006) (2007) (2008) (2009) . The results are shown in Fig. 3 . For statistical significance, only those boxes where the sample number around the 50% probability of drizzle occurrence is larger than 1000 are shown. Generally, the threshold over the globe varies from À 18 to À 13 dBZ. Higher values (4 À 15 dBZ) are mostly located to the west of land masses where marine boundary layer clouds dominate, i.e., off the Californian, Peruvian, Canarian, Namibian and Australian coasts. The globally averaged MaxR value for precipitation threshold is about À 16 dBZ, which is in agreement with the maximum reflectivity threshold of À 15 dBZ as widely used in the literature [CITATION_1] .",
